    <prj:ScienceGoal>
        <prj:name>Centaurus A outer filaments</prj:name>
        <prj:note>  We propose to map the northern filaments of Cen A (20 kpc from the galaxy centre) in the most compact configuration (C34-1, resolution 3.24'', ie 60 pc), in Band 3 in order to observe the CO(1-0) emission along the filaments. We ask for 15 pointings that cover the most interesting part of the filaments. The star forming filaments, that we propose to map, crosses the HI shell observed by Morganti et al. (2004). The edge of the shell, that we propose to map, falls along the jet direction and separate two regimes of feedback where we expect the star formation efficiency to be different.

  First, we aim to see whether the star forming regions inside the filaments follow a resolved Schmidt-Kennicut law (Bigiel et al. 2008) and search for possible deviation. We want to look for morphologically-driven star formation process along the jets.

  Second, we want to determine the large scale dynamics of the gas along the northern filaments and produce the first high resolution map of the gas in the filaments. Recent hydrodynamic simulations studied the evolution of turbulence and star formation in the direction of jet. The spatial resolution and sensitivity of ALMA should see large scale instabilities if present.</prj:note>
