        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>  ALMA can reach a rms of ~4 mJy/beam at 115 GHz in 8 minutes on-source with a spectral resolution of 5 km/s. In the region that we want to observe, Charmandaris et al. (2000) have found a CO(1-0) main beam temperature of 30 mK (0.8 Jy/beam) in the 44''-SEST beam and a linewidth of 50 km/s. That is an integrated sensitivity of 40 Jy.km/s with the SEST 27 Jy/K conversion factor.

  The GALEX and Herschel star forming regions lie in about 60 clumps (r~4.5''). The global SFR for these regions is 2.5x10^{-3} M_sol/yr. Considering the area of these regions, we computed a surface density star formation rate of 2x10^{-3} M_sol/yr/kpc^2. From Bigiel et al. (2008), we derived an expected gas surface density of 10 M_sol/pc^2 for each one of these 60 regions. That gives an integrated sensitivity of 1.2 Jy.km/s, and a peak flux of 60 mJy if the linewidth is 20 km/s.

  Each 60 mJy star forming clump could be resolved in two 3.24'' ALMA beams or not resolved at all if very compact. So the expected signal-to-noise ratio will be of at least S/N&gt;7.5 in the clumpy gas. In addition, 2/3 of the SEST emission seems to lie in an extended emission coming from or within regions where the star formation is quenched or less efficient. This extended part of the emission should be easily recovered by the ACA.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
