    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>  NGC 5128 (also known as Centaurus A) is the most nearby powerful AGN, widely studied at all wavelengths. In the present proposal, we are particularly interested in testing positive AGN feedback, i.e. the star formation activity triggered by the interaction between the jets and the interstellar medium. This phenomenon has been long debated, since AGN are thought to mainly suppress star formation. However  recent numerical simulations have demonstrated that negative feedback is not the only issue, and positive feedback is plausible.

  Molecular gas has been found at a distance of ~20 kpc from the galaxy center, associated to HI shells, through CO line detection at SEST (Charmandaris et al. 2000). The molecular gas lies inside some FIR and UV bright star-forming filaments that are observed in the direction of the radio jets. We propose here to use ALMA to study jet-induced star-formation in the northern filaments of Cen A, through Band 3 CO(1-0) large scale mapping, with a resolution of 3.24''~60 pc. This is the typical scale of GMCs, so ideal to detect the clouds, without resolving them, and derive the star formation efficiency.</prp:abstract>
